00:02:07.910 --> 00:02:10.385
And so you have this combination
of way more information

00:02:10.385 --> 00:02:13.640
than ever and us
having bad habits

00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:14.906
to manage that information.

00:02:14.906 --> 00:02:17.280
And you have a world where it
is both extremely difficult

00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:20.200
to capture attention and to
stand out with your idea,

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:23.780
whether it's a project, it's
a start up, it's a passion,

00:02:23.780 --> 00:02:27.060
it's a charity, and having
it be seen by the world.

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:29.380
And at the same time,
defending our attention

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:31.080
by all of this kind
of information,

00:02:31.080 --> 00:02:33.710
understanding which things are
worth our time and attention.

00:02:33.710 --> 00:02:35.790
And so that's kind of
the reason, the impetus,

00:02:35.790 --> 00:02:39.180
for why I wrote "Captivology."

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:41.990
And "Captivology" is about
the science and the psychology

00:02:41.990 --> 00:02:44.540
of attention, and why we pay
attention to certain people

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:47.460
and products, and how to
utilize that science to capture

00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:48.920
the attention of others.

00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:51.700
And so I'm going to talk a
little bit about the research

00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:54.430
I did for "Captivology"--
over 1,000 research

00:02:54.430 --> 00:02:57.130
studies, interviews
with dozens of PhDs,

00:02:57.130 --> 00:03:00.135
and everybody from Steven
Soderbergh, Adrian Grenier,

00:03:00.135 --> 00:03:02.060
the people behind the
Old Spice campaign,

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:04.660
Sheryl Sandberg,
David Copperfield,

00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:06.380
people across industries.

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:08.690
I'm going to talk about the
three stages of attention

00:03:08.690 --> 00:03:12.360
and my model of attention and,
more importantly, what I call

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:13.770
the seven captivation triggers.

00:03:13.770 --> 00:03:16.020
And these are seven
psychological triggers

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:19.350
that capture attention
across all these stages.

00:03:19.350 --> 00:03:22.830
And so let me get
into attention.

00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:26.270
And so I kind of describe
attention as a bonfire.

00:03:26.270 --> 00:03:28.460
And your goal in
capturing attention

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:31.830
is to walk people
through the three stages,

00:03:31.830 --> 00:03:34.149
is to grow the fire
because you can't just

00:03:34.149 --> 00:03:35.190
start out with a bonfire.

00:03:35.190 --> 00:03:36.590
You have to start
with the spark.

00:03:36.590 --> 00:03:38.131
And then you go
through the kindling.

00:03:38.131 --> 00:03:41.030
And then you go and you finally
get to the logs in the bonfire.

00:03:41.030 --> 00:03:43.710
And so the first stage
is immediate attention.

00:03:43.710 --> 00:03:45.520
The second stage
is short attention.

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:47.290
And the last stage
is long attention.

00:03:47.290 --> 00:03:49.630
And let me explain a little
bit about each stage.

00:03:49.630 --> 00:03:50.750
Stage one.

00:03:50.750 --> 00:03:52.010
Immediate attention.

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:54.110
It is our immediate
and automatic reaction

00:03:54.110 --> 00:03:56.180
to certain sights,
sounds, and stimuli.

00:03:56.180 --> 00:03:58.510
It's how we react if someone
does this, for example.

00:03:58.510 --> 00:04:01.290
[POP]

00:04:01.290 --> 00:04:04.360
I love doing that
every single time.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:07.200
It's how we automatically react
to when there's sights, sounds,

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:08.033
something like that.

00:04:08.033 --> 00:04:10.692
When someone puts a gunshot,
or launches a confetti cannon,

00:04:10.692 --> 00:04:11.900
we're going to pay attention.

00:04:11.900 --> 00:04:14.360
And I'm sorry to the
janitors in a little bit.

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:16.360
But the reason why we
react is because it's

00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:17.610
a defense mechanism.

00:04:17.610 --> 00:04:19.370
We're trying to
protect ourselves.

00:04:19.370 --> 00:04:23.330
Imagine if you had to
think every time a car was

00:04:23.330 --> 00:04:24.570
coming at you.

00:04:24.570 --> 00:04:26.190
We'd be dead human beings.

00:04:26.190 --> 00:04:27.492
We'd be a dead species.

00:04:27.492 --> 00:04:28.950
And so it's a
protection mechanism.

00:04:28.950 --> 00:04:30.670
And you'll see that
a lot of attention

00:04:30.670 --> 00:04:31.960
is a defense mechanism.

00:04:31.960 --> 00:04:35.120
And a lot of it is activating
those defense mechanisms.

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:37.310
The second stage is
from subconscious

00:04:37.310 --> 00:04:41.450
automatic attention to
conscious, directed attention,

00:04:41.450 --> 00:04:44.150
is when we start concentrating
on something like a test,

00:04:44.150 --> 00:04:47.890
or a speaker, or a dress.

00:04:47.890 --> 00:04:50.870
That goddamn dress.

00:04:50.870 --> 00:04:52.730
But it's when we
actually start focusing.

00:04:52.730 --> 00:04:55.080
And it is a kind of
short-term thing.

00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:57.690
And it's run by a system
called working memory.

00:04:57.690 --> 00:05:00.380
And working memory is this
short-term memory system

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:02.730
that processes the
sights and sounds

00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:05.680
around us and the other stimuli
and helps us determine which

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:07.410
things are worth our
time and attention

00:05:07.410 --> 00:05:09.160
and, more importantly,
which things should

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:10.980
be stored in long-term memory.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:14.460
Which leads us-- well, before
I tell you-- very complicated

00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:15.260
system, by the way.

00:05:15.260 --> 00:05:16.801
I won't go through
the entire process

00:05:16.801 --> 00:05:19.290
here, but suffice it to say
it's a very complicated system

00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:20.950
that runs our attention.

00:05:20.950 --> 00:05:24.140
The final stage of attention is
a stage called long attention.

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:25.670
I kind of use Beyonce
as an example.

00:05:25.670 --> 00:05:27.711
It's the difference between
hearing and listening

00:05:27.711 --> 00:05:32.694
to a Beyonce song in the
car and joining the Beyhive

00:05:32.694 --> 00:05:34.610
and becoming a lifelong
fan and buying albums.

00:05:34.610 --> 00:05:36.990
It's the reason why when
Beyonce launched her last album,

00:05:36.990 --> 00:05:38.490
she didn't have to
do any marketing.

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:41.050
She just got to drop it and
suddenly everyone bought it.

00:05:41.050 --> 00:05:43.270
But it's because she earned
long attention over time,

00:05:43.270 --> 00:05:45.770
building those relationships,
building that relationship

00:05:45.770 --> 00:05:48.061
with her audience, building
long attention and interest

00:05:48.061 --> 00:05:49.800
from millions of people.

00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:51.430
And so those three
kind of things

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:54.160
combine to create this
bonfire of attention.

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:57.094
Now how do you build that
bonfire of attention?

00:05:57.094 --> 00:05:58.510
You have to go
through what I call

00:05:58.510 --> 00:05:59.790
the seven captivation triggers.

00:05:59.790 --> 00:06:01.350
And these are seven
psychological triggers

00:06:01.350 --> 00:06:03.320
I discovered over and
over again that came up

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:06.550
in my research that
capture attention

00:06:06.550 --> 00:06:08.820
from immediate attention
to long attention.

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:12.103
So let me tell you about the
first one-- automaticity.

00:06:12.103 --> 00:06:12.830
All right.

00:06:12.830 --> 00:06:14.294
So pop quiz.

00:06:14.294 --> 00:06:16.210
If you're a hitchhiker
on the side of the road

00:06:16.210 --> 00:06:18.543
and you want to have the best
chance of being picked up,

00:06:18.543 --> 00:06:20.270
what color shirt
should you wear?

00:06:20.270 --> 00:06:22.910
Guesses?

00:06:22.910 --> 00:06:24.160
Red, white, I heard.

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:24.900
What else?

00:06:24.900 --> 00:06:26.030
Orange.

00:06:26.030 --> 00:06:26.534
Yellow.

00:06:26.534 --> 00:06:27.450
I've heard everything.

00:06:27.450 --> 00:06:30.310
Actually, usually
someone says "naked."

00:06:30.310 --> 00:06:31.610
You guys aren't dirty enough.

00:06:31.610 --> 00:06:33.870
It's too early in
the day or something?

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:34.500
It's a Monday.

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:35.160
Fair enough.

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:40.470
Maybe during Burning Man.

00:06:40.470 --> 00:06:42.620
So the answer is actually,
it's gender specific.

00:06:42.620 --> 00:06:45.740
If you're a man, on
average, any bright color

00:06:45.740 --> 00:06:48.740
will do because of
the dark backgrounds

00:06:48.740 --> 00:06:51.690
of the black roads, and
the dark green grass,

00:06:51.690 --> 00:06:53.586
and the brown dirt.

00:06:53.586 --> 00:06:55.460
But if you're a woman,
and there was actually

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:58.049
a French scientist who was
like, I'm going to study this.

00:06:58.049 --> 00:07:00.340
He wanted to find out who
would get picked up the most.

00:07:00.340 --> 00:07:02.530
So he had women wear six
different colored shirts.

00:07:02.530 --> 00:07:04.900
And on average, someone
would pull over about 13%

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:05.910
of the time.

00:07:05.910 --> 00:07:08.450
Unless they were wearing
the color red, in which case

00:07:08.450 --> 00:07:11.060
they were picked
up 21% of the time.

00:07:11.060 --> 00:07:14.520
And the reason for that is
actually our subconscious

00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:17.340
associations that we have
with red and romanticism.

00:07:17.340 --> 00:07:20.170
In fact, another study found if
you just put a thick red border

00:07:20.170 --> 00:07:22.770
around a person's face, the
opposite gender, on average,

00:07:22.770 --> 00:07:25.977
we'll rate that person
as more attractive.

00:07:25.977 --> 00:07:27.560
Reason why there's
a red border there.

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:29.893
I also just like having an
excuse to put that picture up

00:07:29.893 --> 00:07:32.020
every time.

00:07:32.020 --> 00:07:33.449
But the opposite
gender will rate

00:07:33.449 --> 00:07:34.740
that person as more attractive.

00:07:34.740 --> 00:07:36.281
And even there was
another study that

00:07:36.281 --> 00:07:38.910
found that if a researcher
is wearing a red shirt,

00:07:38.910 --> 00:07:41.799
a person who doesn't know will
actually sit several inches

00:07:41.799 --> 00:07:42.715
closer to that person.

00:07:42.715 --> 00:07:45.350
It's like an automatic
invitation to be more intimate.

00:07:45.350 --> 00:07:48.280
And so immediate attention
is this automatic response

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:49.540
to different stimuli.

00:07:49.540 --> 00:07:52.800
And it really comes down
to two things-- contrast

00:07:52.800 --> 00:07:54.069
and association.

00:07:54.069 --> 00:07:55.860
And contrast is the
contrast that something

00:07:55.860 --> 00:07:58.890
has with its surroundings, and
association is the subconscious

00:07:58.890 --> 00:08:02.060
associations we have with
a certain color, or symbol,

00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:05.810
or sound, based on our cultural
history, based on our biology,

00:08:05.810 --> 00:08:07.880
based on other factors.

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:10.390
And so a key to capturing
attention with automaticity

00:08:10.390 --> 00:08:12.450
is to use the right
color for the job.

00:08:12.450 --> 00:08:15.180
So example is Amazon.

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:18.010
There's a reason why they use
yellow and orange buttons.

00:08:18.010 --> 00:08:20.550
They have high contrast
with their surroundings,

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:21.952
with white and gray backgrounds.

00:08:21.952 --> 00:08:23.160
And they perform really well.

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:26.230
But most bright colors will
actually perform very well.

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:31.340
However, give me some
word association game.

00:08:31.340 --> 00:08:33.100
Give me words you think
when you see this.

00:08:37.412 --> 00:08:38.870
"Dutch" is usually
the first thing.

00:08:38.870 --> 00:08:40.530
Give me more.

00:08:40.530 --> 00:08:41.570
Anyone else?

00:08:41.570 --> 00:08:44.450
Usually someone says "prison."

00:08:44.450 --> 00:08:46.770
But actually, here's my point.

00:08:46.770 --> 00:08:48.020
AUDIENCE: White collar prison.

00:08:48.020 --> 00:08:49.700
BEN PARR: White
collar-- there you go.

00:08:49.700 --> 00:08:53.710
So orange and yellow actually
have the lowest correlation

00:08:53.710 --> 00:08:54.845
with competence.

00:08:54.845 --> 00:08:56.470
Teal and blue actually
has the highest,

00:08:56.470 --> 00:08:58.800
which is why my cover
has blue and teal on it.

00:08:58.800 --> 00:09:00.390
But think about it.

00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:02.400
If someone like this
walked into most offices,

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:05.160
maybe not Google,
but most offices,

00:09:05.160 --> 00:09:07.339
you'd laugh their
ass out of the room.

00:09:07.339 --> 00:09:08.880
And it's because of
that correlation.

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:10.390
And there's all these kind
of different correlations

00:09:10.390 --> 00:09:12.170
we have with different
colors and sounds.

00:09:12.170 --> 00:09:14.390
In fact, let's talk about smell.

00:09:14.390 --> 00:09:17.410
So this flower, I believe
the Camellia flower,

00:09:17.410 --> 00:09:19.260
was used by Ralph
Lauren in a perfume,

00:09:19.260 --> 00:09:20.710
and it performed really well.

00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:22.850
So like, let's
expand it everywhere.

00:09:22.850 --> 00:09:25.040
So we're going to take
it to South America.

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:28.040
Problem is in South America,
this specific flower

00:09:28.040 --> 00:09:29.440
is used in funerals.

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:32.160
So when you sprayed it on, you
literally smelled like death.

00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:34.060
How do you think that performed?

00:09:34.060 --> 00:09:37.280
Not well is the answer.

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:41.380
Trigger number two-- framing.

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:43.729
And so framing is
that we pay attention

00:09:43.729 --> 00:09:45.770
to things that fall within
our frame of reference

00:09:45.770 --> 00:09:47.310
or don't pay attention
to things because

00:09:47.310 --> 00:09:48.393
of our frame of reference.

00:09:48.393 --> 00:09:51.945
And to describe this, I want
to talk about deodorant.

00:09:54.620 --> 00:09:56.730
Anyone want some free deodorant?

00:09:56.730 --> 00:09:59.570
Specifically, I want to talk
about a teenage entrepreneur

00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:00.650
named Edna Murphy.

00:10:00.650 --> 00:10:03.230
And so in the 1910s,
deodorant wasn't a thing.

00:10:03.230 --> 00:10:05.090
And antiperspirants
weren't a thing.

00:10:05.090 --> 00:10:06.720
In fact, this is
what they literally

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:11.049
used to protect themselves--
cotton pads and dress shields.

00:10:11.049 --> 00:10:13.590
And there were two reasons why
antiperspirants and deodorants

00:10:13.590 --> 00:10:15.190
weren't a popular
thing back then.

00:10:15.190 --> 00:10:16.690
First reason was
that people thought

00:10:16.690 --> 00:10:20.790
it was going to kill you to use
one, to have antiperspirants.

00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:23.060
And it was going to kill you.

00:10:23.060 --> 00:10:25.590
But the bigger and second
reason was because it was not

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:27.120
a thing you talked about.

00:10:27.120 --> 00:10:30.330
Bodily fluids, sweat, any
of that sort of thing,

00:10:30.330 --> 00:10:31.280
it wasn't ladylike.

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:35.660
It was not a thing you talked
about in proper conversation.

00:10:35.660 --> 00:10:39.540
And so Edna Murphy, teenage
entrepreneur, her father,

00:10:39.540 --> 00:10:42.510
a surgeon, invented an
antiperspirant for his hands

00:10:42.510 --> 00:10:44.950
because he wanted to not
sweat doing surgeries.

00:10:44.950 --> 00:10:48.880
And she's like, you know, I
could put those in my armpits.

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:49.960
So she does.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:52.960
And she gets a $500 loan
from her grandfather

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:55.349
and she creates Odo-Ro-No.

00:10:55.349 --> 00:10:56.140
Greatest name ever.

00:10:56.140 --> 00:10:58.357
In fact, I found one.

00:10:58.357 --> 00:10:59.940
I don't think they
make these anymore.

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:01.440
Odo-Ro-No.

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:04.160
So she goes out and
she starts selling

00:11:04.160 --> 00:11:05.912
and she gets a little
bit of traction.

00:11:05.912 --> 00:11:07.370
But she's finding
it very difficult

00:11:07.370 --> 00:11:09.800
to get the product
above that plateau

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:12.230
because of the two reasons
I just told you about.

00:11:12.230 --> 00:11:14.325
Now she had to get past it.

00:11:14.325 --> 00:11:15.700
So what she did
was she teamed up

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:18.340
with a guy named James Webb
Young who would eventually

00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:20.590
become the first chairman
of the Ad Council.

00:11:20.590 --> 00:11:22.170
And together they
decided they had

00:11:22.170 --> 00:11:24.200
to go in and tackle these
frames of reference,

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:25.696
these perceptions people had.

00:11:25.696 --> 00:11:27.320
First, how do you
get people to realize

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:29.450
it will not kill you
to wear antiperspirant.

00:11:29.450 --> 00:11:31.340
Well, it was
invented by a doctor.

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:33.215
And so they really
advertised that fact hard.

00:11:33.215 --> 00:11:35.548
And this is actually one of
the original advertisements.

00:11:35.548 --> 00:11:37.060
And you'll see,
Odo-Ro-No being used

00:11:37.060 --> 00:11:39.860
and recommend by leading
physicians skin specialists.

00:11:39.860 --> 00:11:41.290
That helped double
sales, when we

00:11:41.290 --> 00:11:42.792
started advertising that fact.

00:11:42.792 --> 00:11:44.250
But they still had
the bigger issue

00:11:44.250 --> 00:11:47.580
of how do you get people
to actually talk about it?

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:51.770
And so they put out this ad.

00:11:51.770 --> 00:11:56.140
Now this ad talks very
frankly about body orders.

00:11:56.140 --> 00:11:58.770
It says, "a frank discussion of
a subject too often avoided."

00:11:58.770 --> 00:12:01.395
And it talks about body odor and
how you don't have to have it.

00:12:01.395 --> 00:12:03.530
And how you can use
Odo-Ro-No to fix it.

00:12:03.530 --> 00:12:05.830
By the way, this was in
the most popular magazine

00:12:05.830 --> 00:12:07.260
of the era, of 1919.

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:09.920
Does anyone want to guess
which magazine that is?

00:12:12.621 --> 00:12:13.120
What?

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:13.410
Nope.

00:12:13.410 --> 00:12:13.800
Nope.

00:12:13.800 --> 00:12:14.650
Anyone else want to try?

00:12:14.650 --> 00:12:16.983
I'm going to take some out
to dinner if they guess this.

00:12:16.983 --> 00:12:19.100
No one's ever guessed this.

00:12:19.100 --> 00:12:20.070
No.

00:12:20.070 --> 00:12:24.340
Answer is "Ladies Home Journal."

00:12:24.340 --> 00:12:26.720
And so this was put in
"Ladies Home Journal."

00:12:26.720 --> 00:12:29.090
And when it was put in
"Ladies Home Journal,"

00:12:29.090 --> 00:12:33.291
it was actually one of the most
controversial things if 1919.

00:12:33.291 --> 00:12:35.540
Hundreds of women canceled
their "Ladies Home Journal"

00:12:35.540 --> 00:12:39.310
subscriptions in
protest of this ad.

00:12:39.310 --> 00:12:39.969
But guess what?

00:12:39.969 --> 00:12:41.760
The ad changed people's
frame of reference.

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:44.120
They started actually
talking about deodorants.

00:12:44.120 --> 00:12:46.790
And suddenly it was OK to
talk about antiperspirants.

00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:48.160
And sales went through the roof.

00:12:48.160 --> 00:12:49.680
And a few years
later, Edna Murphy

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:52.130
was able to sell her
company for millions.

00:12:52.130 --> 00:12:55.360
And so what she did was she
adapted her audience's frame

00:12:55.360 --> 00:12:56.360
of reference.

00:12:56.360 --> 00:12:58.960
And she helped re-frame
the conversation.

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:02.150
And Odo-Ro-No did this
by adapting to the fact

00:13:02.150 --> 00:13:04.350
that people were worried
about health concerns

00:13:04.350 --> 00:13:07.210
so they brought in the fact
that a doctor invented it.

00:13:07.210 --> 00:13:08.710
And they re-framed
the conversation

00:13:08.710 --> 00:13:10.580
by making it OK to discuss.

00:13:10.580 --> 00:13:12.320
And so frames of
reference and framing

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:14.585
is this incredible power in
which we can pay attention

00:13:14.585 --> 00:13:16.960
to certain things and not
others based on our backgrounds

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:17.690
and worldview.

00:13:17.690 --> 00:13:21.570
It's the reason why if you
talk about climate change

00:13:21.570 --> 00:13:24.711
or you talk about
vaccines, one group

00:13:24.711 --> 00:13:26.460
is going to have a
very different reaction

00:13:26.460 --> 00:13:27.590
than another.

00:13:27.590 --> 00:13:29.590
And in a funny way, it
does make sense sometimes

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:33.030
because if someone comes
to us and is telling us

00:13:33.030 --> 00:13:36.670
how the earth is flat, why the
fuck should we listen to them?

00:13:36.670 --> 00:13:39.120
It makes sense, but
then sometimes we

00:13:39.120 --> 00:13:42.620
get into this kind of rut
where we miss important things.

00:13:42.620 --> 00:13:45.920
There are a couple ways to
create frames of reference

00:13:45.920 --> 00:13:47.770
and to change
frame of reference.

00:13:47.770 --> 00:13:49.400
One big one is scarcity.

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:53.190
So who likes Twinkies here?

00:13:53.190 --> 00:13:54.650
Oh, thank God.

00:13:54.650 --> 00:13:56.200
No one.

00:13:56.200 --> 00:13:58.210
But Twinkies, as you
probably may remember,

00:13:58.210 --> 00:14:00.085
a few years ago, the
company that owned them,

00:14:00.085 --> 00:14:01.410
Hostess, went bankrupt, right?

00:14:01.410 --> 00:14:04.600
And suddenly, millions of
people went to the stores

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:06.030
to grab these things.

00:14:06.030 --> 00:14:09.350
And it was not for the reason
that they tasted any better.

00:14:09.350 --> 00:14:11.520
They still tasted like shit.

00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:13.189
But suddenly, they
became very popular.

00:14:13.189 --> 00:14:14.730
And the reason,
actually, the science

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:17.360
shows that we assign
higher value to things

00:14:17.360 --> 00:14:18.750
that we feel are scarce.

00:14:18.750 --> 00:14:20.920
Specifically, when
we believe something

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:23.520
is scarce due to
outside circumstances.

00:14:23.520 --> 00:14:25.980
If something is scarce
because it is popular,

00:14:25.980 --> 00:14:27.589
it does not raise
in value and we

00:14:27.589 --> 00:14:28.880
don't pay more attention to it.

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:31.171
But if something is scarce
because of an outside force,

00:14:31.171 --> 00:14:33.150
because of a manufacturing
or some other thing,

00:14:33.150 --> 00:14:34.620
we assign much more value.

00:14:34.620 --> 00:14:37.630
In a Google example, let's
think about Gmail invites.

00:14:37.630 --> 00:14:39.800
I actually, someone paid
me $100 once for one

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:41.460
of my original Gmail invites.

00:14:41.460 --> 00:14:43.590
I was like, why the
f--oh, here you go.

00:14:43.590 --> 00:14:45.450
Thank you for the $100.

00:14:45.450 --> 00:14:48.290
But that scarcity element
does drive attention

00:14:48.290 --> 00:14:51.270
and drives a different
frame of reference.

00:14:51.270 --> 00:14:55.050
Trigger number
three-- disruption.

00:14:55.050 --> 00:14:57.930
We pay attention to the things
that violate our expectations.

00:14:57.930 --> 00:15:00.364
And I'll explain
why in a moment.

00:15:00.364 --> 00:15:01.780
So there's this
one research study

00:15:01.780 --> 00:15:03.570
where they want to
see which things would

00:15:03.570 --> 00:15:04.934
stick in the memory longest.

00:15:04.934 --> 00:15:07.100
And so they would give
subjects different sentences.

00:15:07.100 --> 00:15:10.300
Standard ones like, the
maids were plating the food

00:15:10.300 --> 00:15:13.425
on the table versus
the maid licked

00:15:13.425 --> 00:15:16.110
the ammonia off the floor.

00:15:16.110 --> 00:15:19.020
Now which one do you think
people had a better memory for?

00:15:19.020 --> 00:15:21.610
It's actually a scientific term
called the bizarreness effect.

00:15:21.610 --> 00:15:24.370
And the reason we
remember this is actually

00:15:24.370 --> 00:15:27.460
because of something called
violations expectancy theory.

00:15:27.460 --> 00:15:31.340
So imagine, for example,
we're on a date.

00:15:31.340 --> 00:15:31.840
All right.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:36.740
And we're just like sitting down
and suddenly, two giant clowns

00:15:36.740 --> 00:15:39.160
come and just sit down
right next to us, right?

00:15:39.160 --> 00:15:41.070
We're going to be paying
attention to them.

00:15:41.070 --> 00:15:43.550
But the reason why is because
we make an automatic threat

00:15:43.550 --> 00:15:44.220
assessment.

00:15:44.220 --> 00:15:46.720
We have to figure out whether
this is a positive development

00:15:46.720 --> 00:15:48.504
or we should run the fuck away.

00:15:48.504 --> 00:15:49.920
Maybe this is our
good friends who

00:15:49.920 --> 00:15:51.711
are about to go visit
a children's hospital

00:15:51.711 --> 00:15:54.230
or maybe they're about to mug
us and we're about to die.

00:15:54.230 --> 00:15:56.070
Either way, we're going to
turn our attention to something

00:15:56.070 --> 00:15:58.060
that violates our
expectations because we

00:15:58.060 --> 00:15:59.410
have to protect ourselves.

00:15:59.410 --> 00:16:00.960
If you think about
how we originally

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:03.627
were as hunter gatherers when
our attention was scanning,

00:16:03.627 --> 00:16:05.710
we were looking for things
that were out of place.

00:16:05.710 --> 00:16:09.370
Maybe it's a saber tooth tiger,
maybe it's a potential food.

00:16:09.370 --> 00:16:11.190
We have the same
kind of instincts.

00:16:11.190 --> 00:16:12.898
And that's why we pay
attention to things

00:16:12.898 --> 00:16:14.180
that violate our expectations.

00:16:14.180 --> 00:16:16.554
And there's a couple examples,
especially in advertising,

00:16:16.554 --> 00:16:17.480
that work really well.

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:19.870
This is a campaign a couple
years ago from Patagonia.

00:16:19.870 --> 00:16:20.760
They did a campaign.

00:16:20.760 --> 00:16:23.325
It was called Don't
Buy This Jacket.

00:16:23.325 --> 00:16:24.450
They're a clothing company.

00:16:24.450 --> 00:16:26.370
They're not supposed
to fucking say that.

00:16:26.370 --> 00:16:28.902
But they explain, when
you go into the ad

00:16:28.902 --> 00:16:30.360
deeper for that,
the reason they're

00:16:30.360 --> 00:16:32.080
saying this is
because they don't

00:16:32.080 --> 00:16:34.940
want people to unnecessarily
buy more stuff.

00:16:34.940 --> 00:16:37.390
They want to help repair
your clothing if you can.

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:40.016
And of course, they'll sell you
a jacket if your jacket is old.

00:16:40.016 --> 00:16:41.723
But they'll help you
repair and they want

00:16:41.723 --> 00:16:42.890
to protect the environment.

00:16:42.890 --> 00:16:45.720
Funny enough, this ad telling
people not to buy their stuff

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:48.030
made more people buy
their stuff-- double

00:16:48.030 --> 00:16:49.690
the amount within nine months.

00:16:49.690 --> 00:16:52.160
A whole ton of people
started buying their jackets

00:16:52.160 --> 00:16:53.600
because people paid attention.

00:16:53.600 --> 00:16:55.380
It was a positive experience.

00:16:55.380 --> 00:16:58.010
The Old Spice guy's another
great example of this.

00:16:58.010 --> 00:16:59.810
Of positive destruction.

00:16:59.810 --> 00:17:02.060
Every five seconds diamonds
are suddenly coming out

00:17:02.060 --> 00:17:03.810
of people's hands
and he's suddenly

00:17:03.810 --> 00:17:06.496
on horses and diving into
cakes and who knows what else.

00:17:06.496 --> 00:17:08.329
But it's a very kind
of positive experience.

00:17:08.329 --> 00:17:09.740
And every few
seconds something is

00:17:09.740 --> 00:17:11.114
happening different
that violates

00:17:11.114 --> 00:17:14.119
your expectations of how the
world is supposed to work.

00:17:14.119 --> 00:17:16.849
The disruption has to match your
values is a very key thing I

00:17:16.849 --> 00:17:17.920
want to mention.

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:19.859
There is such a
thing as positive

00:17:19.859 --> 00:17:20.965
versus negative attention.

00:17:20.965 --> 00:17:23.089
I think about what Nationwide
did at the Super Bowl

00:17:23.089 --> 00:17:23.400
commercial.

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:25.066
And the only thing I
think of Nationwide

00:17:25.066 --> 00:17:27.339
now is that
Nationwide kills kids.

00:17:27.339 --> 00:17:32.050
Now I'm going to show you the
actual ad from a few years ago.

00:17:32.050 --> 00:17:34.450
This one.

00:17:34.450 --> 00:17:36.560
This was an ad for Quiznos.

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:41.550
And they had weird, freaky,
mutant, fucking rodents

00:17:41.550 --> 00:17:43.560
advertising sandwiches.

00:17:43.560 --> 00:17:47.760
Why the fuck would you want any
of these things near your food?

00:17:47.760 --> 00:17:52.270
How does that make
any sense at all?

00:17:52.270 --> 00:17:55.670
And yet, a bunch
of execs decide,

00:17:55.670 --> 00:17:58.000
you know what, this is
going to be a great idea.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:17:59.700
They went bankrupt last year.

00:17:59.700 --> 00:18:01.860
There is such a thing
as negative attention.

00:18:01.860 --> 00:18:02.990
This make no sense at all.

00:18:02.990 --> 00:18:04.350
It did not match their values.

00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:05.100
It was disruptive.

00:18:05.100 --> 00:18:06.390
People paid attention.

00:18:06.390 --> 00:18:08.620
But it didn't make people
buy their sandwiches.

00:18:08.620 --> 00:18:11.120
There is a clear difference.

00:18:11.120 --> 00:18:14.530
Trigger number four-- reward.

00:18:14.530 --> 00:18:16.780
And so I learned some
interesting things

00:18:16.780 --> 00:18:18.800
about the reward
mechanisms of the brain.

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:20.640
Most people think of
dopamine as the system

00:18:20.640 --> 00:18:24.170
that creates pleasure but that's
actually a misunderstanding.

00:18:24.170 --> 00:18:26.710
I interviewed Dr. Kent
Barich, a leading researcher

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:31.240
in dopamine and reward
systems of the brain.

00:18:31.240 --> 00:18:33.130
And what he did is
this famous experiment

00:18:33.130 --> 00:18:35.880
where he took the
dopamine out of lab mice

00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:38.249
and he wanted to see
what would happen.

00:18:38.249 --> 00:18:40.790
And what he found was that the
mice could still feel pleasure

00:18:40.790 --> 00:18:42.220
even with no dopamine.

00:18:42.220 --> 00:18:44.000
If you gave the
mouse sugar water,

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.570
it would still find pleasure
drinking the sugar water.

00:18:46.570 --> 00:18:50.000
What happened though was that
the mice lost all motivation.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.420
These mice were so demotivated,
in fact, that they would rather

00:18:54.420 --> 00:18:56.730
starve to death than eat.

00:18:56.730 --> 00:18:59.770
And almost all of them died
because they had no motivation

00:18:59.770 --> 00:19:02.970
to live or to find
any kind of survival.

00:19:02.970 --> 00:19:06.340
And so dopamine actually
creates wanting.

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:08.760
It creates a wanting
response in the brain.

00:19:08.760 --> 00:19:10.670
Opioids actually create
the actual pleasure.

00:19:10.670 --> 00:19:12.890
But when it comes to
attention, what's important

00:19:12.890 --> 00:19:14.310
is our desire for something.

00:19:14.310 --> 00:19:17.790
We pay attention to
when we desire a reward,

00:19:17.790 --> 00:19:20.890
whether it is an intrinsic
or extrinsic reward.

00:19:20.890 --> 00:19:23.060
Extrinsic rewards are
the kind of physical ones

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:27.030
that you're very well familiar
with-- money, food, sex.

00:19:27.030 --> 00:19:29.070
Very, very, clear things.

00:19:29.070 --> 00:19:31.610
And they really do capture our
attention in the short term.

00:19:31.610 --> 00:19:33.151
In fact, there was
a study that found

00:19:33.151 --> 00:19:36.210
that if you associate an
object with monetary gain,

00:19:36.210 --> 00:19:38.080
with money, even
just a few cents,

00:19:38.080 --> 00:19:41.520
people's eyes will automatically
gravitate towards that object,

00:19:41.520 --> 00:19:45.780
even after that object is no
longer associated with money.

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:47.700
But that's only
short term attention.

00:19:47.700 --> 00:19:49.220
Short attention.

00:19:49.220 --> 00:19:51.450
That doesn't capture
attention over the long term.

00:19:51.450 --> 00:19:54.160
Intrinsic rewards capture
attention over the long term.

00:19:54.160 --> 00:19:57.830
Things like self satisfaction
and purpose and mastery

00:19:57.830 --> 00:20:00.620
and these kind of
self type of things

00:20:00.620 --> 00:20:04.240
that motivate us in our jobs,
in our careers, in our lives.

00:20:04.240 --> 00:20:06.590
And family and order
and whatever things that

00:20:06.590 --> 00:20:07.132
motivate you.

00:20:07.132 --> 00:20:08.548
Those are the kinds
of things that

00:20:08.548 --> 00:20:09.790
make people stay long term.

00:20:09.790 --> 00:20:12.810
You need both to capture
and maintain attention.

00:20:12.810 --> 00:20:15.840
But you can't just use one
or the other and succeed.

00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:18.040
And there are a couple
ways to create motivation

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:20.930
and to create
desire for a reward.

00:20:20.930 --> 00:20:22.950
One is the power of surprise.

00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:25.615
And so a couple years ago,
a company called Skopje,

00:20:25.615 --> 00:20:26.990
they wanted to
get more engineers

00:20:26.990 --> 00:20:29.450
because it is obviously a
very, very competitive market.

00:20:29.450 --> 00:20:32.400
And so they're like, how do
we get some more engineers?

00:20:32.400 --> 00:20:34.810
They're going to offer a bonus
of $11,000 for signing up.

00:20:34.810 --> 00:20:35.870
That's kind standard.

00:20:35.870 --> 00:20:37.020
But they decided,
you know, what we're

00:20:37.020 --> 00:20:38.680
going to parody the most
interesting man in the world

00:20:38.680 --> 00:20:39.480
campaign.

00:20:39.480 --> 00:20:42.285
So they wrapped $11,000
in cash in bacon.

00:20:42.285 --> 00:20:43.660
And then they
would also give you

00:20:43.660 --> 00:20:47.300
Macoun 15, a oil
painting of yourself,

00:20:47.300 --> 00:20:51.290
and my favorite, a harpoon gun.

00:20:51.290 --> 00:20:54.520
I don't know about you,
but I want a harpoon gun.

00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:55.710
Can I get a harpoon gun?

00:20:55.710 --> 00:20:56.600
That would be nice.

00:20:56.600 --> 00:21:00.860
So this actually, this
campaign, got them

00:21:00.860 --> 00:21:02.510
over 1,000 different
applications.

00:21:02.510 --> 00:21:04.770
And they were able to fill
their engineering seats.

00:21:04.770 --> 00:21:07.719
And so that surprise actually
helps capture attention

00:21:07.719 --> 00:21:08.760
when it comes to rewards.

00:21:08.760 --> 00:21:10.820
But it's also just the
fact of surprising people

00:21:10.820 --> 00:21:11.725
with a reward.

00:21:11.725 --> 00:21:13.100
And so there was
a study that was

00:21:13.100 --> 00:21:16.196
done-- there was a
study that what happened

00:21:16.196 --> 00:21:17.570
was that they
would have subjects

00:21:17.570 --> 00:21:19.170
and they would
spray either water

00:21:19.170 --> 00:21:20.910
or citrus into their mouths.

00:21:20.910 --> 00:21:24.440
And what they found was that
the people who could not

00:21:24.440 --> 00:21:27.030
predict the order in which
citrus or water were going

00:21:27.030 --> 00:21:29.850
to be sprayed into the mouths
felt much more pleasure,

00:21:29.850 --> 00:21:32.370
had stronger member of
the task, and overall

00:21:32.370 --> 00:21:33.560
paid more attention.

00:21:33.560 --> 00:21:36.450
It was a much more positive
and pleasant experience.

00:21:36.450 --> 00:21:40.130
And so most people deliver
rewards in incentive form.

00:21:40.130 --> 00:21:42.120
You do this, I'll give you this.

00:21:42.120 --> 00:21:44.720
And that is actually the least
effective type of reward.

00:21:44.720 --> 00:21:47.450
There many other better
types are rewards.

00:21:47.450 --> 00:21:49.370
There's a company
called Keep and what

00:21:49.370 --> 00:21:52.430
they do is they specialize
in post action rewards.

00:21:52.430 --> 00:21:54.730
And what happens is
like, you do a task.

00:21:54.730 --> 00:21:57.520
Like you run two miles, you
get a high score in a game,

00:21:57.520 --> 00:22:01.100
and suddenly something
pops up being like,

00:22:01.100 --> 00:22:02.466
you've accomplished something.

00:22:02.466 --> 00:22:03.590
We want to give you a gift.

00:22:03.590 --> 00:22:04.910
A surprise gift.

00:22:04.910 --> 00:22:07.080
Maybe it's a Gatorade,
maybe it's an extra life,

00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:08.330
maybe it's some points.

00:22:08.330 --> 00:22:10.920
But that kind of surprise,
where people didn't expect

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:13.100
to get a reward
actually reinforces

00:22:13.100 --> 00:22:15.300
behavior much
stronger and increases

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:18.450
attention and overall
is much stronger

00:22:18.450 --> 00:22:19.670
when it comes to attention.

00:22:19.670 --> 00:22:23.170
Practically every other type
of reward delivery is better.

00:22:23.170 --> 00:22:25.990
Gifting, for example--
you're very used to it,

00:22:25.990 --> 00:22:28.940
like in a social game being able
to give a life to your friends.

00:22:28.940 --> 00:22:30.784
Even though, as
you think about it,

00:22:30.784 --> 00:22:32.950
you're not actually giving
anything to your friends.

00:22:32.950 --> 00:22:34.590
It's actually coming
from the game.

00:22:34.590 --> 00:22:37.610
It just makes it look
like it's coming from you.

00:22:37.610 --> 00:22:39.500
But it actually creates
much more attention

00:22:39.500 --> 00:22:42.220
because it feels like it's a
more personal sort of thing.

00:22:42.220 --> 00:22:44.320
Sneaky.

00:22:44.320 --> 00:22:48.080
Trigger number
five-- reputation.

00:22:48.080 --> 00:22:51.080
So I'm going to put this on
while we talk about reputation

00:22:51.080 --> 00:22:52.440
in this interesting study.

00:22:52.440 --> 00:22:55.530
So a few years ago, there was
a study at Emory University

00:22:55.530 --> 00:22:59.430
and what they did
was they looked

00:22:59.430 --> 00:23:02.365
at the FMRIs of
students' brains as they

00:23:02.365 --> 00:23:04.350
were making economic decisions.

00:23:04.350 --> 00:23:06.910
I'm putting on a lab coat.

00:23:06.910 --> 00:23:08.700
I'll explain why in a moment.

00:23:08.700 --> 00:23:10.660
So they were looking at
the FMRIs of students

00:23:10.660 --> 00:23:12.076
and they were
trying to figure out

00:23:12.076 --> 00:23:14.770
how the brain works while during
decision making in economics.

00:23:14.770 --> 00:23:16.922
And so they would have to
make economic decisions

00:23:16.922 --> 00:23:17.630
with their money.

00:23:17.630 --> 00:23:19.962
And as you could expect, the
critical thinking decision

00:23:19.962 --> 00:23:21.420
centers of the
brain would light up

00:23:21.420 --> 00:23:23.628
whenever they were making
decisions with their money.

00:23:23.628 --> 00:23:25.210
And this is the
actual brain scans.

00:23:25.210 --> 00:23:27.730
But in half the cases, they
would have an expert come in

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:28.670
to give advice.

00:23:28.670 --> 00:23:30.280
In this case, an
economics professor.

00:23:30.280 --> 00:23:32.320
And it would always be
the conservative advice.

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:34.850
And what they found was
when a subject was listening

00:23:34.850 --> 00:23:37.960
to the expert, the decision
making centers of their brain

00:23:37.960 --> 00:23:39.710
would completely shut off.

00:23:39.710 --> 00:23:41.860
It was as if they offloaded
the processing power

00:23:41.860 --> 00:23:44.970
of their brains to the expert.

00:23:44.970 --> 00:23:48.130
And in fact, even
when the advice

00:23:48.130 --> 00:23:51.520
that the expert was
giving was clearly wrong,

00:23:51.520 --> 00:23:56.120
the subjects would more often go
with that advice than the other

00:23:56.120 --> 00:23:57.530
because they're not thinking.

00:23:57.530 --> 00:24:00.209
And this is a phenomenon
known as directed deference.

00:24:00.209 --> 00:24:02.250
And directed deference
helps drive our attention.

00:24:02.250 --> 00:24:04.780
And so the reputation
triggers that we pay attention

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:08.620
to repeatable sources,
specifically authority figures,

00:24:08.620 --> 00:24:11.130
the crowd, and most
of all, experts.

00:24:11.130 --> 00:24:14.300
In fact, and this
is a fun study,

00:24:14.300 --> 00:24:17.505
if someone puts on a doctor's
coat and you tell them

00:24:17.505 --> 00:24:20.000
it's a doctor's coat,
and they do tasks,

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.670
on average they will
have better attention,

00:24:22.670 --> 00:24:25.570
they will make less mistakes,
and they will complete tasks

00:24:25.570 --> 00:24:26.990
more effectively.

00:24:26.990 --> 00:24:29.070
Now if you give them
the very same coat

00:24:29.070 --> 00:24:30.910
and you tell them
it's a painter's coat,

00:24:30.910 --> 00:24:33.540
their attention will actually
go in the opposite direction.

00:24:33.540 --> 00:24:35.830
And they will
complete less tasks

00:24:35.830 --> 00:24:37.490
and they'll be less effective.

00:24:37.490 --> 00:24:42.120
The mere perception of
expertise increases attention.

00:24:42.120 --> 00:24:44.750
That's why I'm wearing the coat.

00:24:44.750 --> 00:24:47.070
And so as I said before,
there are three key types

00:24:47.070 --> 00:24:50.650
of reputable sources
that we pay attention to.

00:24:50.650 --> 00:24:52.516
Authority figures
have power over us

00:24:52.516 --> 00:24:54.140
and so we pay attention
as long as they

00:24:54.140 --> 00:24:55.510
have that power over us.

00:24:55.510 --> 00:24:57.850
And the crowd kind of
acts like an expert.

00:24:57.850 --> 00:25:00.930
And you think about sites
like Yelp or a lot of others

00:25:00.930 --> 00:25:03.534
where we go into those
the sites for ratings

00:25:03.534 --> 00:25:04.950
and we trust their
ratings because

00:25:04.950 --> 00:25:06.700
of the collective
knowledge of the crowd.

00:25:06.700 --> 00:25:09.150
And we trust the crowd.

00:25:09.150 --> 00:25:11.890
So there's another reason why
we trust reputable sources

00:25:11.890 --> 00:25:12.690
and experts.

00:25:12.690 --> 00:25:15.190
And the answer is actually
from this Edelmen Trust Survey.

00:25:15.190 --> 00:25:17.970
We trust them more than any
other type of spokesperson.

00:25:17.970 --> 00:25:21.200
And so you can see here the
most credible spokesperson out

00:25:21.200 --> 00:25:24.110
of thousands and thousands of
people surveyed are experts.

00:25:24.110 --> 00:25:29.470
More than people like
you, more than executives,

00:25:29.470 --> 00:25:31.970
and definitely more than CEOs.

00:25:31.970 --> 00:25:33.871
We really, really trust experts.

00:25:33.871 --> 00:25:36.120
And government officials are
somewhere in the basement

00:25:36.120 --> 00:25:38.530
where they belong.

00:25:38.530 --> 00:25:40.360
And so key brands and
capturing attention

00:25:40.360 --> 00:25:42.600
really revolves around
leveraging experts,

00:25:42.600 --> 00:25:44.700
and leveraging the
power of experts,

00:25:44.700 --> 00:25:46.770
and establishing your
credibility as an expert

00:25:46.770 --> 00:25:48.740
as well.

00:25:48.740 --> 00:25:51.236
Odo-Ro-No did this by
leveraging the fact that it

00:25:51.236 --> 00:25:52.235
was created by a doctor.

00:25:55.837 --> 00:25:58.170
And leveraging the fact that
it was created by a doctor.

00:25:58.170 --> 00:25:59.900
And this is also the
same kind of reason

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:03.950
why things like Kickstarter
do very well because it's

00:26:03.950 --> 00:26:07.050
the crowd's expertise showing
that a specific thing is

00:26:07.050 --> 00:26:08.700
worth our attention and time.

00:26:08.700 --> 00:26:10.060
Two more triggers.

00:26:10.060 --> 00:26:11.040
Trigger number six.

00:26:11.040 --> 00:26:12.130
I can take this coat off.

00:26:12.130 --> 00:26:14.020
It's kinda hot.

00:26:14.020 --> 00:26:16.414
I'm stripping for you all.

00:26:16.414 --> 00:26:18.320
You're welcome.

00:26:18.320 --> 00:26:19.840
Mystery.

00:26:19.840 --> 00:26:22.940
So what movie is this?

00:26:22.940 --> 00:26:24.590
Anyone want to guess?

00:26:24.590 --> 00:26:26.080
That's right. "Cloverfield."

00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:28.572
So I don't have time to
show the entire trailer

00:26:28.572 --> 00:26:29.280
of "Cloverfield."

00:26:29.280 --> 00:26:34.100
But in the first trailer of
"Cloverfield," what happens

00:26:34.100 --> 00:26:38.120
is there's people at a party,
suddenly there's a roar

00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:40.630
and then the Statue of Liberty's
head falls into the street.

00:26:40.630 --> 00:26:42.050
There's no mention
of the movie's name

00:26:42.050 --> 00:26:43.720
or what it's called
or what it's about.

00:26:43.720 --> 00:26:46.000
And this is a huge impetus
of the mystery trigger.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:47.680
And this is a JJ Abrams movie.

00:26:47.680 --> 00:26:49.220
He's a master at mysteries.

00:26:49.220 --> 00:26:51.781
At both using mysteries to
market his material because

00:26:51.781 --> 00:26:54.030
for example, we know barely
anything about "Star Wars"

00:26:54.030 --> 00:26:55.390
and that's what he wants.

00:26:55.390 --> 00:26:57.970
And also in his storytelling.

00:26:57.970 --> 00:27:01.030
For "Lost," for example, famous
for having that cliffhanger

00:27:01.030 --> 00:27:03.410
that would get people to
come back week to week.

00:27:03.410 --> 00:27:05.710
And so there are actually
two scientific reasons why

00:27:05.710 --> 00:27:07.196
mysteries capture attention.

00:27:07.196 --> 00:27:09.320
The first is something
called the Zeigarnik Effect.

00:27:09.320 --> 00:27:11.730
So in the 1950s, there was
this Soviet researcher.

00:27:11.730 --> 00:27:12.910
Her name is Bluma Zeigarnik.

00:27:12.910 --> 00:27:15.940
And she is sitting
in a restaurant

00:27:15.940 --> 00:27:18.920
and she's curious
about something.

00:27:18.920 --> 00:27:20.600
The waiters who are
taking her order

00:27:20.600 --> 00:27:23.020
have perfect memory
of her orders

00:27:23.020 --> 00:27:25.250
until they actually drop
it off over at the kitchen,

00:27:25.250 --> 00:27:27.540
and suddenly, completely forget.

00:27:27.540 --> 00:27:29.400
Now why is that?

00:27:29.400 --> 00:27:30.060
She's curious.

00:27:30.060 --> 00:27:32.670
So she gets a bunch of
students and a bunch of kids

00:27:32.670 --> 00:27:34.370
and she has them do puzzles.

00:27:34.370 --> 00:27:38.320
But in half the case studies,
she takes their puzzles away.

00:27:38.320 --> 00:27:40.072
That's mean, right?

00:27:40.072 --> 00:27:41.780
A couple months later,
she would ask them

00:27:41.780 --> 00:27:43.425
which puzzles they
would remember.

00:27:43.425 --> 00:27:44.050
And guess what.

00:27:44.050 --> 00:27:45.660
The only puzzles
they could remember,

00:27:45.660 --> 00:27:47.080
the only tasks
they could remember

00:27:47.080 --> 00:27:48.980
were the ones that
were incomplete.

00:27:48.980 --> 00:27:51.620
We have a much stronger memory
for incomplete the tasks,

00:27:51.620 --> 00:27:54.460
incomplete thoughts,
incomplete storylines.

00:27:54.460 --> 00:27:55.790
Zeigarnik Effect.

00:27:55.790 --> 00:27:58.159
Now there's a second reason.

00:27:58.159 --> 00:27:59.950
Now, let's pretend you
and I are on a date.

00:27:59.950 --> 00:28:01.374
Actually, we'll go on a date.

00:28:01.374 --> 00:28:02.540
We've been on a date before.

00:28:02.540 --> 00:28:04.290
So pretend we're on a date.

00:28:04.290 --> 00:28:07.150
Now if we're on a first
date, what we're going to do,

00:28:07.150 --> 00:28:08.920
typically, is small talk, right?

00:28:08.920 --> 00:28:12.080
Kind of things like where are
you from, what do you like,

00:28:12.080 --> 00:28:13.270
that sort of thing.

00:28:13.270 --> 00:28:16.610
And the reason why we do that
is actually because of a thing

00:28:16.610 --> 00:28:19.220
called uncertainty
reduction principal.

00:28:19.220 --> 00:28:21.800
And essentially, we don't
like uncertainty in our lives.

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:23.030
It makes us uncomfortable.

00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:24.800
And we meet a stranger, there's
nothing but uncertainly.

00:28:24.800 --> 00:28:26.536
We don't know anything
about each other.

00:28:26.536 --> 00:28:27.910
And so what we're
trying to do is

00:28:27.910 --> 00:28:30.350
relieve the uncertainty so we
can figure out whether or not

00:28:30.350 --> 00:28:31.808
I want to hang out
with this person

00:28:31.808 --> 00:28:35.210
or be friends or get the
fuck away as far as I can.

00:28:35.210 --> 00:28:37.310
All depends, right?

00:28:37.310 --> 00:28:39.460
And so in the case of
uncertainty reduction

00:28:39.460 --> 00:28:41.520
principle, it applies
all across the board.

00:28:41.520 --> 00:28:43.156
When we're left
with a cliffhanger

00:28:43.156 --> 00:28:44.530
and we're left
with a mystery, we

00:28:44.530 --> 00:28:46.230
want to relieve
that uncertainty.

00:28:46.230 --> 00:28:47.809
We want to resolve
that storyline.

00:28:47.809 --> 00:28:49.600
And then when we don't,
we start filling it

00:28:49.600 --> 00:28:52.532
in with speculation
and uncertainty.

00:28:52.532 --> 00:28:54.240
The Malaysian Airlines
disaster last year

00:28:54.240 --> 00:28:56.120
is a perfect example of this.

00:28:56.120 --> 00:28:59.630
It's not the first
time a plane went down.

00:28:59.630 --> 00:29:01.780
But planes aren't
supposed to disappear.

00:29:01.780 --> 00:29:04.040
And so when this
one disappeared,

00:29:04.040 --> 00:29:06.410
suddenly, it was on
the media for months.

00:29:06.410 --> 00:29:07.094
Why?

00:29:07.094 --> 00:29:08.510
Because we don't
like uncertainty,

00:29:08.510 --> 00:29:10.210
so we start filling
with speculation.

00:29:10.210 --> 00:29:11.000
Especially CNN.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:12.890
They loved filling
it with speculation.

00:29:12.890 --> 00:29:14.190
Thank you, CNN.

00:29:14.190 --> 00:29:16.320
And they kept filling it
with all this speculation.

00:29:16.320 --> 00:29:17.320
Trying to-- what's going on?

00:29:17.320 --> 00:29:17.850
Where did it go?

00:29:17.850 --> 00:29:18.690
All that sort of thing.

00:29:18.690 --> 00:29:20.648
And the reason, again,
why is because we do not

00:29:20.648 --> 00:29:22.390
like that uncertainty.

00:29:22.390 --> 00:29:23.940
We have to fill it in.

00:29:23.940 --> 00:29:25.850
It's the same reason
also why, for example, I

00:29:25.850 --> 00:29:29.240
don't know if anyone remembers
a year ago, Justine Sacco.

00:29:29.240 --> 00:29:32.220
She was an exec at IAC.

00:29:32.220 --> 00:29:34.650
And she before she
gets on the plane she

00:29:34.650 --> 00:29:37.234
decides to tweet something
along the lines of "I'm

00:29:37.234 --> 00:29:37.900
going to Africa.

00:29:37.900 --> 00:29:38.830
Hope I don't get AIDS.

00:29:38.830 --> 00:29:39.470
Oh and wait.

00:29:39.470 --> 00:29:40.760
I'm white."

00:29:40.760 --> 00:29:41.650
She does this.

00:29:41.650 --> 00:29:42.890
She gets on a plane.

00:29:42.890 --> 00:29:44.210
And then she's off Wi-Fi.

00:29:44.210 --> 00:29:45.690
By the time she
gets off the plane,

00:29:45.690 --> 00:29:47.690
she's the number one
trending topic in the world

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:49.880
and she's the most
reviled person on Twitter.

00:29:49.880 --> 00:29:52.070
And the reason why is
because she couldn't

00:29:52.070 --> 00:29:53.450
close the uncertainty gap.

00:29:53.450 --> 00:29:55.150
She couldn't close
the mystery loop.

00:29:55.150 --> 00:29:56.410
Everyone started
filling speculation

00:29:56.410 --> 00:29:57.380
of how is she going to react?

00:29:57.380 --> 00:29:58.350
Who is this person?

00:29:58.350 --> 00:29:59.670
Why would she say such a thing?

00:29:59.670 --> 00:30:02.770
In fact, Steve Martin
tweeted something offensive

00:30:02.770 --> 00:30:04.770
as well in the same
time period but nothing

00:30:04.770 --> 00:30:06.850
happened to him because
he was able to delete

00:30:06.850 --> 00:30:10.260
his Tweet within two
minutes and post an apology.

00:30:10.260 --> 00:30:12.300
Mystery done.

00:30:12.300 --> 00:30:14.020
Justine Sacco could
not and that's

00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:16.605
why she became the number
one trending topic.

00:30:16.605 --> 00:30:19.230
And so there are a couple things
when you think about mysteries

00:30:19.230 --> 00:30:20.200
to capture attention.

00:30:20.200 --> 00:30:21.220
The mystery trigger.

00:30:21.220 --> 00:30:22.680
One is to create suspense.

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:24.305
And I don't think
the sound is working,

00:30:24.305 --> 00:30:27.290
but we're going to
try a video anyway.

