Like that guy.

00:31:40.380 --> 00:31:42.780
So everyone knows that
guy or most of you

00:31:42.780 --> 00:31:43.840
know that guy, maybe.

00:31:43.840 --> 00:31:45.210
And this is Brian Williams.

00:31:45.210 --> 00:31:50.320
And what happened with
him was he basically

00:31:50.320 --> 00:31:53.700
lied about what happened
when he was in the war zone.

00:31:53.700 --> 00:31:56.830
And he put out what amounted
to a half-assed apology.

00:31:56.830 --> 00:31:59.430
It was kind of like, "I sort
of mis-remembered, blah, blah,

00:31:59.430 --> 00:31:59.930
blah."

00:31:59.930 --> 00:32:02.110
What it didn't do was
complete the mystery gap

00:32:02.110 --> 00:32:03.610
and complete the mystery.

00:32:03.610 --> 00:32:06.090
And so people filled in with
speculation until suddenly,

00:32:06.090 --> 00:32:11.180
more reports came out to a
point where he had to step down.

00:32:11.180 --> 00:32:15.130
On the other hand, regardless
of what you think of this guy,

00:32:15.130 --> 00:32:16.640
there was no mystery gap.

00:32:16.640 --> 00:32:18.240
When his allegations
came out, he

00:32:18.240 --> 00:32:21.120
came out hard and being like,
here's exactly fact ABC.

00:32:21.120 --> 00:32:21.640
Go look.

00:32:21.640 --> 00:32:22.140
That's it.

00:32:22.140 --> 00:32:22.966
Done.

00:32:22.966 --> 00:32:23.590
And guess what?

00:32:23.590 --> 00:32:24.400
He still has a job.

00:32:24.400 --> 00:32:26.600
Again, regardless of
what you think of him,

00:32:26.600 --> 00:32:28.730
he's still in his chair
and Brian Williams is not.

00:32:28.730 --> 00:32:30.730
But there's actually a
couple good tech examples

00:32:30.730 --> 00:32:31.730
of this as well.

00:32:31.730 --> 00:32:34.540
So a couple years
ago, Airbnb-- I

00:32:34.540 --> 00:32:37.290
don't know if anyone remembers
this-- but they had a renter.

00:32:37.290 --> 00:32:39.576
They had a gal named EJ and
she rented out her place

00:32:39.576 --> 00:32:41.200
and she came back
and it was completely

00:32:41.200 --> 00:32:44.770
ransacked-- destroyed,
burned, everything stolen.

00:32:44.770 --> 00:32:47.730
And Airbnb was kind of
slow to helping her our

00:32:47.730 --> 00:32:49.250
in fixing the problem.

00:32:49.250 --> 00:32:51.610
So she wrote a
blog post about it.

00:32:51.610 --> 00:32:52.620
It went viral.

00:32:52.620 --> 00:32:53.890
Everyone wrote about it.

00:32:53.890 --> 00:32:57.520
And when it started
going viral, Airbnb

00:32:57.520 --> 00:32:58.760
felt like it had to respond.

00:32:58.760 --> 00:33:02.030
So Brian Chesky wrote
that on Hacker News, which

00:33:02.030 --> 00:33:04.160
basically says, "hi, everyone.

00:33:04.160 --> 00:33:06.690
We were shocked when we heard
about this unsettling event.

00:33:06.690 --> 00:33:08.340
We have been working closely
with the authorities, blah,

00:33:08.340 --> 00:33:09.600
blah, blah, blah.

00:33:09.600 --> 00:33:11.531
It is written by a lawyer.

00:33:11.531 --> 00:33:12.530
It sounds like a lawyer.

00:33:12.530 --> 00:33:13.590
There is no apology.

00:33:13.590 --> 00:33:16.100
It doesn't resolve jack shit.

00:33:16.100 --> 00:33:17.210
Guess what?

00:33:17.210 --> 00:33:19.040
The mystery continued.

00:33:19.040 --> 00:33:20.600
EJ put out another post.

00:33:20.600 --> 00:33:22.560
The thing went more viral.

00:33:22.560 --> 00:33:24.990
Airbnb looked even worse
until finally, they

00:33:24.990 --> 00:33:26.470
put out the right statement.

00:33:26.470 --> 00:33:29.960
They put out this blog post.

00:33:29.960 --> 00:33:33.480
This one, which said, like,
with EJ, we got this wrong.

00:33:33.480 --> 00:33:34.370
We let her down.

00:33:34.370 --> 00:33:35.410
And we are sorry.

00:33:35.410 --> 00:33:36.720
And we fucked up.

00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:38.690
And here's how we're
going to fix it.

00:33:38.690 --> 00:33:40.900
When they did that,
the story was over

00:33:40.900 --> 00:33:42.860
because they completed
the mystery loop,

00:33:42.860 --> 00:33:47.709
the gap of uncertainty was
filled and the story died.

00:33:47.709 --> 00:33:49.750
And so when it comes to
a press crisis like that,

00:33:49.750 --> 00:33:52.240
your number one goal
is to end the mystery.

00:33:52.240 --> 00:33:55.490
Exactly here is we
fucked up and here's

00:33:55.490 --> 00:33:57.510
how we're going to fix it.

00:33:57.510 --> 00:33:58.600
Final trigger.

00:33:58.600 --> 00:34:00.516
And then questions, if
you have any questions.

00:34:00.516 --> 00:34:01.824
Think about your questions now.

00:34:01.824 --> 00:34:02.490
Acknowledgement.

00:34:02.490 --> 00:34:05.400
The most powerful of my
captivation triggers.

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:09.211
And so there was this
one study that-- yeah,

00:34:09.211 --> 00:34:10.460
it was pretty cruel, actually.

00:34:10.460 --> 00:34:13.370
And what they did was
they strapped electrodes

00:34:13.370 --> 00:34:16.449
to the ankles of married women.

00:34:16.449 --> 00:34:18.207
Yeah, pretty much.

00:34:18.207 --> 00:34:19.540
And there were three conditions.

00:34:19.540 --> 00:34:22.159
Condition one.

00:34:22.159 --> 00:34:23.750
Married woman sitting alone.

00:34:23.750 --> 00:34:25.030
Condition two.

00:34:25.030 --> 00:34:29.000
Married woman could hold
the hand of a stranger.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:30.000
Condition three.

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:32.530
Married woman could hold
the hand of her husband.

00:34:32.530 --> 00:34:35.920
And so what they
found was that when

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:39.598
the married women who had
no one to hold the hand of

00:34:39.598 --> 00:34:41.389
felt the most pain
because they had nowhere

00:34:41.389 --> 00:34:43.210
to direct their attention.

00:34:43.210 --> 00:34:46.510
And the married women who
could hold the husband's hands

00:34:46.510 --> 00:34:48.254
felt the least pain
because they had

00:34:48.254 --> 00:34:50.420
someone they love to direct
their attention towards.

00:34:50.420 --> 00:34:52.520
But what I found
fascinating about this study

00:34:52.520 --> 00:34:55.300
was that there was
a direct correlation

00:34:55.300 --> 00:34:58.240
between the strength of the
marriage and the amount of pain

00:34:58.240 --> 00:34:59.590
that these women felt.

00:34:59.590 --> 00:35:03.040
The more connected they felt
to their spouse, the less pain

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:03.850
they felt.

00:35:03.850 --> 00:35:07.120
And it kind of shows how
powerful this acknowledgement

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:08.850
and this connection is.

00:35:08.850 --> 00:35:10.600
This connection is so
powerful that it can

00:35:10.600 --> 00:35:13.180
reduce an even eliminate pain.

00:35:13.180 --> 00:35:15.250
And so the key to the
acknowledgement trigger

00:35:15.250 --> 00:35:17.500
is that we pay attention to
the people and things that

00:35:17.500 --> 00:35:20.250
pay attention to us and
provide us with validation,

00:35:20.250 --> 00:35:23.050
empathy, and understanding.

00:35:23.050 --> 00:35:25.469
And one example of
this is actually

00:35:25.469 --> 00:35:26.510
in our celebrity culture.

00:35:26.510 --> 00:35:29.280
And so this is Adrian Grenier
from the show "Entourage"

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:30.850
and this is Dr.
Thomas de Zengotita.

00:35:30.850 --> 00:35:32.800
And I interviewed them
for "Captivology."

00:35:32.800 --> 00:35:35.341
And you wouldn't think that they
would be experts in anything

00:35:35.341 --> 00:35:37.890
like this, but actually, they
did a documentary together

00:35:37.890 --> 00:35:44.870
called "Teenage Paparazzo" on
a 15-year-old teenage paparazzi

00:35:44.870 --> 00:35:47.079
and following him
around and exploring

00:35:47.079 --> 00:35:49.120
why we pay attention to
celebrities and celebrity

00:35:49.120 --> 00:35:49.940
culture.

00:35:49.940 --> 00:35:52.110
And we had this long
conversation about why.

00:35:52.110 --> 00:35:53.060
And we kind of came
to the conclusion,

00:35:53.060 --> 00:35:55.460
one of the major reasons we
pay attention to celebrities

00:35:55.460 --> 00:35:57.930
is because they're, in a way,
a reflection of ourselves.

00:35:57.930 --> 00:36:00.270
They are a piece
of our identity.

00:36:00.270 --> 00:36:02.380
It says something about
you, whether you're

00:36:02.380 --> 00:36:06.280
a fan of Justin
Bieber or Rachel Ray

00:36:06.280 --> 00:36:10.150
or Sheryl Sandberg or
an Apple or a Google

00:36:10.150 --> 00:36:12.450
or a whichever company.

00:36:12.450 --> 00:36:15.019
It says something about
you and your identity.

00:36:15.019 --> 00:36:16.810
And we are looking for
things that validate

00:36:16.810 --> 00:36:19.780
our identity in some way.

00:36:19.780 --> 00:36:22.380
In fact, actually,
Buzzfeed, for example--

00:36:22.380 --> 00:36:24.710
I interviewed Jonah
Peretti the CEO Buzzfeed--

00:36:24.710 --> 00:36:26.760
and what I learned
from them is that they

00:36:26.760 --> 00:36:28.980
do a lot of this kind
of validation aspect.

00:36:28.980 --> 00:36:30.730
One article that I
read about is that they

00:36:30.730 --> 00:36:33.220
did was "54 Things
That Minnesotans Are

00:36:33.220 --> 00:36:35.270
Too Humble To Brag About."

00:36:35.270 --> 00:36:38.770
Now, this article went viral,
especially in Minnesota,

00:36:38.770 --> 00:36:39.810
as you could imagine.

00:36:39.810 --> 00:36:41.226
But the reason why
is because it's

00:36:41.226 --> 00:36:44.420
a validation, a positive
affirmation of a key identity,

00:36:44.420 --> 00:36:45.870
for a key demographic.

00:36:45.870 --> 00:36:48.570
And it's saying it's great
to be from Minnesota.

00:36:48.570 --> 00:36:51.160
And Buzzfeed puts these
articles and these quizzes

00:36:51.160 --> 00:36:52.510
out all the time.

00:36:52.510 --> 00:36:58.367
'90s Kids or from Chicago
or works in X industry.

00:36:58.367 --> 00:36:59.450
They do this all the time.

00:36:59.450 --> 00:37:00.699
And it's always very positive.

00:37:00.699 --> 00:37:01.610
They affirm.

00:37:01.610 --> 00:37:03.550
They go for EQ over IQ.

00:37:03.550 --> 00:37:07.869
And it works really well for
capturing attention for them.

00:37:07.869 --> 00:37:09.535
So there's actually
a term for all this,

00:37:09.535 --> 00:37:12.060
and especially for our
relationship with celebrities.

00:37:12.060 --> 00:37:14.210
It's called the
parasocial relationship.

00:37:14.210 --> 00:37:16.970
And so it is our capability
to feel a two-way relationship

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:18.730
with a one-way figure.

00:37:18.730 --> 00:37:20.920
And I'll give an example.

00:37:20.920 --> 00:37:23.900
There is-- my old
boss at "Mashable,"

00:37:23.900 --> 00:37:25.610
she works for Rachel Ray now.

00:37:25.610 --> 00:37:28.130
And what happened
was Rachael Ray

00:37:28.130 --> 00:37:31.660
came out for Obamacare, right?

00:37:31.660 --> 00:37:33.716
And what suddenly
happened was there

00:37:33.716 --> 00:37:36.090
was a whole bunch of women
who came out and they're like,

00:37:36.090 --> 00:37:37.730
how could you do this?

00:37:37.730 --> 00:37:39.690
You've betrayed me.

00:37:39.690 --> 00:37:42.420
I thought I knew you.

00:37:42.420 --> 00:37:43.290
The fuck?

00:37:43.290 --> 00:37:45.660
How does this make any sense?

00:37:45.660 --> 00:37:47.370
It makes sense
because people can

00:37:47.370 --> 00:37:50.230
feel as deep of a
connection with a figure

00:37:50.230 --> 00:37:53.040
like that as they can with their
best friend or their families.

00:37:53.040 --> 00:37:54.510
Parasocial relationship.

00:37:54.510 --> 00:37:57.000
It's why we can fall
in love with a brand

00:37:57.000 --> 00:37:59.119
or a musician or an artist.

00:37:59.119 --> 00:38:00.910
And the case, for
example, of Taylor Swift.

00:38:00.910 --> 00:38:03.290
She's a master at
parasocial relationships.

00:38:03.290 --> 00:38:05.630
So last year, she was
doing YouTube videos.

00:38:05.630 --> 00:38:08.320
And it was YouTube videos
of her wrapping gifts

00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:10.310
and sending it to
a few of her fans.

00:38:10.310 --> 00:38:13.410
And this created a frenzy
in her entire community.

00:38:13.410 --> 00:38:16.640
She didn't have to give a
gift to every single member

00:38:16.640 --> 00:38:20.550
of her community, to all
over fans-- just a few

00:38:20.550 --> 00:38:23.530
to show that she cared
about them as a collective.

00:38:23.530 --> 00:38:25.910
And as a result, they
paid attention back

00:38:25.910 --> 00:38:29.120
and made her album the number
one album of last year.

00:38:29.120 --> 00:38:31.490
She did a fantastic job
of building that community

00:38:31.490 --> 00:38:32.820
and building that relationship.

00:38:32.820 --> 00:38:35.475
And she scaled her relationship
with her community.

00:38:35.475 --> 00:38:36.850
Now there are a
couple other ways

00:38:36.850 --> 00:38:39.530
to build that kind of
identity and that validation

00:38:39.530 --> 00:38:42.360
and that acknowledgement.

00:38:42.360 --> 00:38:43.980
And it is this way.

00:38:43.980 --> 00:38:45.990
It is through the
power of participation.

00:38:45.990 --> 00:38:47.530
So some of you may
know this story.

00:38:47.530 --> 00:38:52.400
In the 1950s, Betty Crocker
and all the big cake mixing

00:38:52.400 --> 00:38:56.120
and food mixing companies at
the time like Duncan Hines

00:38:56.120 --> 00:38:59.400
and Pillsbury, they were trying
to get cake mix off the ground.

00:38:59.400 --> 00:39:02.450
But cake mix wasn't taking off
with the female demographic,

00:39:02.450 --> 00:39:04.020
not like Bisquik did.

00:39:04.020 --> 00:39:06.239
And they were stumped.

00:39:06.239 --> 00:39:07.780
Betty Crocker's
like, why is this not

00:39:07.780 --> 00:39:10.230
being getting
bought by everybody.

00:39:10.230 --> 00:39:11.710
So they brought
in two researchers

00:39:11.710 --> 00:39:14.230
to come in and give them
advice on what's going on.

00:39:14.230 --> 00:39:15.960
And they figured
it out, actually.

00:39:15.960 --> 00:39:21.520
The reason why it wasn't
taking off was eggs.

00:39:21.520 --> 00:39:24.574
Now back then, eggs actually
came in powdered form.

00:39:24.574 --> 00:39:26.990
You could just have the powdered
eggs, you just put it in.

00:39:26.990 --> 00:39:28.500
You didn't have to have
the fresh eggs with you.

00:39:28.500 --> 00:39:30.690
And in fact, if you
actually try these recipes,

00:39:30.690 --> 00:39:32.190
there really isn't
much a difference

00:39:32.190 --> 00:39:35.230
between a powdered
egg and a fresh egg.

00:39:35.230 --> 00:39:38.020
But what they found
was that women

00:39:38.020 --> 00:39:40.070
didn't feel like
they were making

00:39:40.070 --> 00:39:43.580
any contribution to the recipe
in the cake mix version.

00:39:43.580 --> 00:39:46.650
And so what Betty Crocker
did was literally make

00:39:46.650 --> 00:39:49.210
their product harder to use.

00:39:49.210 --> 00:39:51.840
And the result was that their
sales went through the roof

00:39:51.840 --> 00:39:53.780
and they won the
cake mixing wars

00:39:53.780 --> 00:39:58.170
by making it so that you had
to break eggs into the recipe.

00:39:58.170 --> 00:40:00.442
And it worked
really, really well

00:40:00.442 --> 00:40:01.900
because they enabled
their audience

00:40:01.900 --> 00:40:04.430
to participate and provide
some kind of validation,

00:40:04.430 --> 00:40:05.890
to provide their input.

00:40:05.890 --> 00:40:07.640
It's the same kind of
reason, for example,

00:40:07.640 --> 00:40:11.250
why Kickstarter is so powerful.

00:40:11.250 --> 00:40:12.250
Yes, Exploding Kittens.

00:40:12.250 --> 00:40:13.730
I can't wait to get my deck.

00:40:13.730 --> 00:40:16.360
And it's because not just
are you buying something--

00:40:16.360 --> 00:40:18.040
it's pretty much
a buying website--

00:40:18.040 --> 00:40:21.730
but you feel like that you're
providing some kind of input.

00:40:21.730 --> 00:40:24.574
You are helping a company
get off the ground.

00:40:24.574 --> 00:40:25.990
You are providing
something extra.

00:40:25.990 --> 00:40:27.850
You are part of that community.

00:40:27.850 --> 00:40:30.654
A couple years ago, I remember,
Vitamin Water-- they actually

00:40:30.654 --> 00:40:32.070
asked their community
to help name

00:40:32.070 --> 00:40:34.600
the next flavor of Vitamin
Water and actually create

00:40:34.600 --> 00:40:35.440
the next flavor.

00:40:35.440 --> 00:40:38.330
And it was a campaign
and it went really viral.

00:40:38.330 --> 00:40:40.455
And they allowed their
audience to put their input.

00:40:40.455 --> 00:40:42.246
And they eventually
came up with one called

00:40:42.246 --> 00:40:43.790
"Connect," based off Facebook.

00:40:43.790 --> 00:40:47.450
And it did really well and
their sales went up as a result,

00:40:47.450 --> 00:40:49.840
again because they allowed
their community to participate

00:40:49.840 --> 00:40:52.270
and that alone created
that acknowledgement

00:40:52.270 --> 00:40:54.180
with their audience.

00:40:54.180 --> 00:40:57.130
And so I've talked about
the seven key triggers.

00:40:57.130 --> 00:41:00.760
Automaticity, framing,
disruption, reward, reputation,

00:41:00.760 --> 00:41:02.251
mystery, and acknowledgement.

00:41:02.251 --> 00:41:03.750
And you'll kind of
notice that these

00:41:03.750 --> 00:41:06.490
triggers go across all
three stages of attention.

00:41:06.490 --> 00:41:09.205
Automaticity is very powerful
in immediate attention,

00:41:09.205 --> 00:41:11.580
while disruption is a very
powerful trigger for capturing

00:41:11.580 --> 00:41:14.720
short attention, while mysteries
and acknowledgement are

00:41:14.720 --> 00:41:16.800
powerful tools for
long attention,

00:41:16.800 --> 00:41:18.542
get people to have
long term interest.

00:41:18.542 --> 00:41:20.000
Because it's not
enough to just get

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:22.510
people to pay attention
to your ad or to your idea

00:41:22.510 --> 00:41:23.680
or to your campaign.

00:41:23.680 --> 00:41:28.810
But you need people to become
customers and users and fans.

00:41:28.810 --> 00:41:31.130
And the last thing I
will say that I learned

00:41:31.130 --> 00:41:33.850
from this process is
from all the interviews

00:41:33.850 --> 00:41:36.350
I did with all these
masters of attention

00:41:36.350 --> 00:41:41.330
is that the masters of attention
don't try to capture attention

00:41:41.330 --> 00:41:42.605
for themselves.

00:41:42.605 --> 00:41:44.730
They're trying to get
attention for their products,

00:41:44.730 --> 00:41:46.640
their projects, and their ideas.

00:41:46.640 --> 00:41:48.810
They're not trying
to be me, me, me.

00:41:48.810 --> 00:41:51.820
They're trying to get a cause
and to promote something

00:41:51.820 --> 00:41:53.930
that is bigger and beyond them.

00:41:53.930 --> 00:41:56.880
And that is a much more powerful
version and much more powerful

00:41:56.880 --> 00:41:58.880
form of attention.

00:41:58.880 --> 00:42:01.500
And I guess that is a
sign that it's done.

00:42:01.500 --> 00:42:03.320
So you know what?

00:42:03.320 --> 00:42:04.824
Thank you, very much.

