00:44:24.420 --> 00:44:25.310
BEN PARR: Exactly.

00:44:25.310 --> 00:44:26.550
One of the people I
interviewed and one

00:44:26.550 --> 00:44:28.380
of my favorite
interviews for the book,

00:44:28.380 --> 00:44:30.650
is Shigeru Miyamoto, the
creator of Super Mario.

00:44:30.650 --> 00:44:33.360
And I got to interview
him at E3 a few years ago.

00:44:33.360 --> 00:44:36.610
And he talked me
through why Mario

00:44:36.610 --> 00:44:38.809
captures so much attention
across all three stages.

00:44:38.809 --> 00:44:40.350
So I don't know if
you all know this,

00:44:40.350 --> 00:44:42.810
but the original Super
Mario, when they first

00:44:42.810 --> 00:44:45.312
created the character, they
only had 16 by 16 pixels.

00:44:45.312 --> 00:44:47.770
And they're like, how do we
make this guy more distinctive?

00:44:47.770 --> 00:44:49.910
How do we have him
pop out on the screen?

00:44:49.910 --> 00:44:52.540
Well, we got to make his nose
big because that's the only way

00:44:52.540 --> 00:44:54.320
to see he even has a nose.

00:44:54.320 --> 00:44:55.936
So they made his nose big.

00:44:55.936 --> 00:44:57.310
But you couldn't
even tell he had

00:44:57.310 --> 00:44:59.840
a nose so they put a
mustache on it so you

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:01.340
could define the nose.

00:45:01.340 --> 00:45:04.560
Now it was impossible to
do hair in 16 by 16 pixels.

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:06.450
So we're going to
give him a red cap.

00:45:06.450 --> 00:45:09.050
And a shirt didn't really pop
out at all, shirt and pants,

00:45:09.050 --> 00:45:10.390
so they gave him overalls.

00:45:10.390 --> 00:45:15.020
And that's actually why Super
Mario has big nose, moustache,

00:45:15.020 --> 00:45:17.190
a hat, and overalls.

00:45:17.190 --> 00:45:18.700
But that's just
immediate attention.

00:45:18.700 --> 00:45:21.100
They really focused on that
kind of gameplay element,

00:45:21.100 --> 00:45:23.510
getting people to try to
achieve the reward of getting

00:45:23.510 --> 00:45:24.968
that high score,
getting to the end

00:45:24.968 --> 00:45:26.940
of that level, and that
loop every single time,

00:45:26.940 --> 00:45:28.490
within a specific game.

00:45:28.490 --> 00:45:32.330
But the reason why we play every
Mario game and love and all

00:45:32.330 --> 00:45:34.205
that sort of thing is
because we fall in love

00:45:34.205 --> 00:45:35.120
with the characters.

00:45:35.120 --> 00:45:37.980
We know the key elements
of every single Mario game.

00:45:37.980 --> 00:45:39.460
There's always
going to be Koopas.

00:45:39.460 --> 00:45:41.400
There's always going
to be gold coins.

00:45:41.400 --> 00:45:43.586
There's always going to
be a Bowser somewhere.

00:45:43.586 --> 00:45:45.960
And that kind of element makes
us come back for each game

00:45:45.960 --> 00:45:47.260
because we have the familiarity.

00:45:47.260 --> 00:45:49.426
While each game is different
enough in terms of game

00:45:49.426 --> 00:45:52.360
play to make us
find something new.

00:45:52.360 --> 00:45:55.770
Whether it's going to a Mario
galaxy or a new platform

00:45:55.770 --> 00:45:56.910
or that sort of thing.

00:45:56.910 --> 00:45:58.420
And so that's part
of why Mario has

00:45:58.420 --> 00:46:01.080
become an icon over decades.

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:04.580
And so many other games
have fallen by the wayside.

00:46:04.580 --> 00:46:06.430
AUDIENCE: I am wondering
what suggestions

00:46:06.430 --> 00:46:09.490
you have for getting people to
pay attention to and not only

00:46:09.490 --> 00:46:11.310
pay attention to,
but take action

00:46:11.310 --> 00:46:13.840
in regard to
environmental issues,

00:46:13.840 --> 00:46:17.120
such as water conservation
and climate change.

00:46:17.120 --> 00:46:18.750
BEN PARR: Oh.

00:46:18.750 --> 00:46:19.890
Oh.

00:46:19.890 --> 00:46:21.951
I mean, I went through a
lot of framing research

00:46:21.951 --> 00:46:22.950
to think about that one.

00:46:22.950 --> 00:46:24.991
Because there's a couple
things that go about it.

00:46:24.991 --> 00:46:26.930
It's really a
framing issue, right?

00:46:26.930 --> 00:46:32.300
It's elevating the
importance of that knowledge

00:46:32.300 --> 00:46:34.930
to a level where people will be
forced to pay attention, right?

00:46:34.930 --> 00:46:36.304
Because there's
a whole-- there's

00:46:36.304 --> 00:46:39.470
a segment of the population
that absolutely and thank

00:46:39.470 --> 00:46:42.030
God believes that we
have huge issues coming

00:46:42.030 --> 00:46:44.654
with water conservation
and climate change.

00:46:44.654 --> 00:46:46.070
And yet, there's
still a huge part

00:46:46.070 --> 00:46:47.930
of the population
that will not even

00:46:47.930 --> 00:46:51.240
listen to you if you mention
these things because they have

00:46:51.240 --> 00:46:55.390
been indoctrinated
with years of hearing

00:46:55.390 --> 00:46:57.340
a different side of the story.

00:46:57.340 --> 00:46:59.850
Now there's a couple different
ways to kind of go about it.

00:46:59.850 --> 00:47:02.058
You can find a way to adapt
to the frame of reference

00:47:02.058 --> 00:47:04.140
and not go directly and
be like, you're wrong.

00:47:04.140 --> 00:47:05.730
Because that will
actually not work.

00:47:05.730 --> 00:47:07.820
You have to find a
way to get actually

00:47:07.820 --> 00:47:10.510
them to agree on a little thing
and that actually opens up

00:47:10.510 --> 00:47:11.839
the door lot more.

00:47:11.839 --> 00:47:13.630
You get them to agree
on the smallest thing

00:47:13.630 --> 00:47:15.730
and that will make them
more receptive to an idea.

00:47:15.730 --> 00:47:16.620
There's a couple other things.

00:47:16.620 --> 00:47:17.800
One interesting
thing I learned is

00:47:17.800 --> 00:47:19.070
the illusion of truth effect.

00:47:19.070 --> 00:47:21.230
And this might not necessarily
help you get attention for it,

00:47:21.230 --> 00:47:22.605
but it'll help
you understand why

00:47:22.605 --> 00:47:24.400
people believe what they do.

00:47:24.400 --> 00:47:27.760
And it is purely that the
more you repeat a phrase,

00:47:27.760 --> 00:47:30.690
the more likely people
will believe it is true.

00:47:30.690 --> 00:47:32.660
And they did a study
where they would

00:47:32.660 --> 00:47:38.040
have people go through like
30 or 40 phrases every couple

00:47:38.040 --> 00:47:40.360
weeks and they would
rate how true they were.

00:47:40.360 --> 00:47:43.600
And every time they
went through it,

00:47:43.600 --> 00:47:46.130
they would rate the statements
that they saw over and over

00:47:46.130 --> 00:47:48.800
again as more true,
despite the fact

00:47:48.800 --> 00:47:50.280
that repeating a
statement does not

00:47:50.280 --> 00:47:52.880
make a thing more or less true.

00:47:52.880 --> 00:47:54.880
But it actually has that
kind of profound effect

00:47:54.880 --> 00:47:56.780
in our brains and our minds.

00:47:56.780 --> 00:47:58.890
And so when it comes
to getting attention

00:47:58.890 --> 00:48:00.576
for that sort of
thing, it's going

00:48:00.576 --> 00:48:01.700
through those three stages.

00:48:01.700 --> 00:48:03.430
It's how do you get
people to pay attention

00:48:03.430 --> 00:48:04.471
to it in the first place?

00:48:04.471 --> 00:48:06.900
If they don't know anything
about it, disruption trigger.

00:48:06.900 --> 00:48:08.910
Getting people to violate
their expectations

00:48:08.910 --> 00:48:10.993
with something that'll
make them turn their heads.

00:48:10.993 --> 00:48:13.440
I think about anti
smoking campaigns.

00:48:13.440 --> 00:48:16.210
In Thailand, they
had a campaign where

00:48:16.210 --> 00:48:19.100
they had little kids with
cigarettes in their mouths,

00:48:19.100 --> 00:48:22.400
asking adults for lights that
had cigarettes in their mouths.

00:48:22.400 --> 00:48:24.990
And the adults would be like,
you shouldn't be smoking.

00:48:24.990 --> 00:48:26.230
It's causes cancer.

00:48:26.230 --> 00:48:28.840
And the kids would be like,
then why are you smoking it?

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:32.040
And that went viral not just
in Thailand but all across

00:48:32.040 --> 00:48:33.920
because it violated
people's expectations,

00:48:33.920 --> 00:48:36.050
and it really drove
the point home.

00:48:36.050 --> 00:48:37.890
But then, it kind of
comes in long term.

00:48:37.890 --> 00:48:40.223
It depends on the audience
that you're really going for.

00:48:40.223 --> 00:48:42.670
I suspect that you
have a huge group.

00:48:42.670 --> 00:48:45.240
There's one group that just
will not believe what you say.

00:48:45.240 --> 00:48:47.050
And it's going to
require different tactics

00:48:47.050 --> 00:48:49.290
and you have to really think
about the framing trigger.

00:48:49.290 --> 00:48:51.520
And you have this audience
that thinks it's important

00:48:51.520 --> 00:48:53.590
but maybe they're not
being active enough.

00:48:53.590 --> 00:48:55.532
And they know that
there's sort of a problem,

00:48:55.532 --> 00:48:57.240
but they don't think
of it strong enough.

00:48:57.240 --> 00:48:59.760
And I think that maybe have
to violate their expectations

00:48:59.760 --> 00:49:02.470
and jolt them out of their
complacency and be like, here

00:49:02.470 --> 00:49:04.264
is what is effing happening.

00:49:04.264 --> 00:49:05.930
And I'm not sure what
that kind of thing

00:49:05.930 --> 00:49:08.672
is but you need to jolt them
out of their expectations.

00:49:08.672 --> 00:49:10.130
I would love to
talk about that one

00:49:10.130 --> 00:49:12.213
further because that's a
hard problem that I still

00:49:12.213 --> 00:49:15.560
haven't fully figured out
how we solve that one.

